            "1543-ERJX-5860",
            "Using Custom Source Subtitles",
            '<p style="font-family: Verdana;">How do I install custom subtitles for any Source game?</p>',
            '<h2>Compiled (.DAT) Files</h2>    <p>  \tIf you already have a compiled <tt><tt>closecaption_<i>&lt;language&gt;</i>.dat</tt></tt> file, simply copy the file to the following location:  </p>    <p>  \t<i><b>NOTE:</b> The <tt>\\Steam\\</tt> folder is located in <tt>C:\\Program Files\\</tt> or <tt>C:\\Program Files (x86)\\</tt> by default.</i>  </p>  \t  <ul>  \t<li>  \t\t<tt>\\Steam\\steamapps\\[Steam account name]\\[game name]\\[modname]\\resource\\</tt>  \t</li>  </ul>    <p>  \tFor example, for Half-Life 2, the path would be:  </p>  \t  <ul>  \t<li>  \t\t<tt>\\Steam\\steamapps\\[Steam account name]\\half-life 2\\hl2\\resource\\</tt>  \t</li>  </ul>    <br />    <p>  \tThen, start the game and ensure closed captioning is enabled in the Options > Audio menu.  </p>    <p>  \tTo change to the custom language, open the <a href="/kb_article.php?ref=3041-SHZN-9384">console</a> and enter the following command:  </p>    <ul>  \t<li>  \t\tcc_lang <i>&lt;language&gt;</i>  \t</li>  </ul>    <br />    <p>  \tWhere <i>&lt;language&gt;</i> is the same as the language in the closed caption file name.  </p>    <h2>Uncompiled (.TXT) Files</h2>    <p>  \tText files must be compiled before they will work with Source games. If you have a closecaption_<i>&lt;language&gt;</i>.txt file, then you will need to do the following to compile it:  </p>    <ol>  \t<li>  \t\tInstall the <a href="/kb_article.php?ref=1987-WYGJ-3701">Source SDK</a> from the Tools section of the Steam Library.  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tOpen the Source SDK launcher and ensure you have the correct game selected.  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tNavigate to the Source SDK <tt>\\bin\\</tt> folder:  \t\t<ul>  \t\t\t<li>  \t\t\t\t<tt>\\Steam\\steamapps\\[Steam account name]\\sourcesdk\\bin\\</tt>  \t\t\t</li>  \t\t</ul>  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tDetermine which version of the Source engine the game uses, then open that folder. In most cases this will be <tt>\\orangebox\\</tt>  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tOpen the <tt>\\bin\\</tt> subfolder of the engine folder. Inside this folder should be a program named <tt>captioncompiler.exe</tt>  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tTake your closecaption_<i>&lt;language&gt;</i>.txt file, then drag it onto the <tt>captioncompiler.exe</tt> program. A file called <tt>closecaption_<i>&lt;language&gt;</i>.dat</tt> should appear &mdash; this is your compiled caption file.  \t</li>  \t<li>  \t\tFollow the instructions under <i><b>Compiled (.DAT) Files</b></i> using this file.  \t</li>  </ol>    <h2>Creating Translations</h2>    <p>  \tIf you would like to translate closed captions into your own language, please see the following Valve Developer Wiki article on this topic:  </p>    <p>  \t<a href="http://developer.valvesoftware.com/wiki/Closed_Captions"><b>Closed Captions</b></a>  </p>',
